Write an Arduino/ Raspberry pi program for interfacing with PIR sensor Experiment


* **PIR Sensor** = Passive Infrared Sensor
  It detects **infrared radiation** emitted by humans or animals.
* When motion is detected ‚Üí the PIR sensor **outputs HIGH (1)**
  When no motion ‚Üí **outputs LOW (0)**

We use this to **trigger** actions ‚Äî like turning ON a light or buzzer, sending a message, etc.

---

## ‚öôÔ∏è Components Required (in Tinkercad or hardware)

| Component         | Quantity | Description              |
| ----------------- | -------- | ------------------------ |
| Arduino Uno R3    | 1        | Microcontroller          |
| PIR Motion Sensor | 1        | Motion detector          |
| LED               | 1        | Indicator light          |
| Resistor (220Œ©)   | 1        | Current limiting for LED |
| Jumper wires      | few      | Connections              |

---

## üîå Wiring Diagram

| PIR Pin | Connects To       | Description              |
| ------- | ----------------- | ------------------------ |
| **VCC** | +5V               | Power supply             |
| **OUT** | Digital Pin **2** | Output signal to Arduino |
| **GND** | GND               | Ground                   |

| LED Pin               | Connects To    |
| --------------------- | -------------- |
| Long leg (anode +)    | Pin **13**     |
| Short leg (cathode ‚Äì) | Resistor ‚Üí GND |

---

## üíª Arduino Code (PIR + LED Alert)

```cpp
// PIR Sensor Interfacing Experiment
const int pirPin = 2;     // PIR sensor output pin
const int ledPin = 13;    // LED pin

int pirState = LOW;       // stores current PIR status
int val = 0;              // read value from sensor

void setup() {
  pinMode(ledPin, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(pirPin, INPUT);
  Serial.begin(9600);
  Serial.println("PIR Sensor Test Initialized...");
  delay(2000); // sensor stabilization
}

void loop() {
  val = digitalRead(pirPin);  // read PIR sensor

  if (val == HIGH) {          // motion detected
    digitalWrite(ledPin, HIGH);
    if (pirState == LOW) {
      Serial.println("‚ö†Ô∏è Motion Detected!");
      pirState = HIGH;
    }
  } 
  else {                      // no motion
    digitalWrite(ledPin, LOW);
    if (pirState == HIGH) {
      Serial.println("No Motion.");
      pirState = LOW;
    }
  }
}
```

---

## ‚ñ∂Ô∏è Running in Tinkercad

1. Add **Arduino Uno** and **PIR sensor** from the component list.
2. Wire it as per the table above.
3. Add **1 LED + resistor** on pin 13.
4. Paste the code and click **Start Simulation**.
5. In simulation, **click on the PIR sensor** ‚Äî
   then toggle ‚ÄúDetects motion‚Äù ‚Üí **ON** ‚Üí LED lights up and ‚ÄúMotion Detected!‚Äù appears in Serial Monitor.

---

## üí° Output

| Motion          | LED | Serial Output         |
| --------------- | --- | --------------------- |
| No motion       | OFF | ‚ÄúNo Motion.‚Äù          |
| Motion detected | ON  | ‚Äú‚ö†Ô∏è Motion Detected!‚Äù |

